body:
First a bit of an explanation of the bug.

Not sure if it's a bug, or the way I'm doing things is incorrect.

So we have an index, lets say called Events. Inside this index is a bunch of documents that look partially like below:

```json
{
    "startTime": "2017-03-15T00:55:00Z",
    "startTimeEpoch": 1489539300,
    "title": "Training Program",
    "trainer": "S Smith",
    "link": "/event/training-program/12345"
}
```

Now I'm trying to hook it up so that users can search these events. I have a custom MultiRange component to allow filtering based on some named days (today, tomorrow, Friday, Saturday and Sunday) with the last 3 days being the correct named days compared to now.

My component looks like below:

```js
import cx from 'classnames';
import React from 'react';
import { connectMultiRange } from 'react-instantsearch/connectors';

class DayList extends React.Component {
    /**
     * This will apply the provided refinement for the day list.
     *
     * This will either set the date range or if user has clicked the selected item it will remove that refinement.
     *
     * The value is in the form of `${item.min}:${item.max}`
     *
     * @param {string} value
     */
    handleFacetItemClick(value) {
        if (value === this.props.currentRefinement) {
            this.props.refine();
        } else {
            this.props.refine(value);
        }
    }

    render() {
        // only get the refinable facet items which are the ones valid to facet against
        const refinableFacetItemsToShow = this.state.items && this.state.items.filter((facetItem) => (!facetItem.noRefinement));

        const items = refinableFacetItemsToShow && refinableFacetItemsToShow.map((facetItem) => {
            return (
                <div className="srp-facet-item" title={item.label} onClick={this.handleFacetItemClick}>
                    <label className="srp-facet-item__name">
                        { item.label }
                    </label>
                </div>
            );
        });

        return (
            <div className="srp-facet">
                <div className="srp-facet__header">
                    <h1 className="srp-facet__header-title">
                        Days
                    </h1>
                </div>

                <div className={facetItemClasses}>
                    {items}
                </div>
            </div>
        );
    }
}

export default connectMultiRange(DayList);
```

Then used as:

```js
const items = [
    {"label":"Today","start":1489496400,"end":1489582800},
    {"label":"Tomorrow","start":1489582800,"end":1489669200},
    {"label":"Friday","start":1489669200,"end":1489755600},
    {"label":"Saturday","start":1489755600,"end":1489842000},
    {"label":"Sunday","start":1489842000,"end":1489928400}
];

<DayList items={items} attributeName="startTimeEpoch" />
```

This works as intended, showing the correct days passed in, but it has an issue when it comes to setting the `noRefinement` property on each of the items accessed by `this.props.items` in the `DayList` component.

**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**
Report a bug

**Bug: What is the current behavior?**
When I have one Event which has `startTimeEpoch: 1489497400` (falls within Today) and then one event that has `startTimeEpoch: 1489846000` (falls within Sunday), then I currently see all items with the `noRefinement` property set to false so all items show up in my filter list.

```json
[
    {"label":"Today","value":"1489496400:1489582800","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":false},
    {"label":"Tomorrow","value":"1489582800:1489669200","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":false},
    {"label":"Friday","value":"1489669200:1489755600","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":false},
    {"label":"Saturday","value":"1489755600:1489842000","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":false},
    {"label":"Sunday","value":"1489842000:1489928400","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":false}
]
```

**Bug: What is the expected behavior?**
When I have one Event which has `startTimeEpoch: 1489497400` (falls within Today) and then one event that has `startTimeEpoch: 1489846000` (falls within Sunday), then I should see the `noRefinement` property set to false on items with a label of Tomorrow, Friday and Saturday with the items with a label of Today and Sunday having a `noRefinement` property set to true.

```json
[
    {"label":"Today","value":"1489496400:1489582800","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":false},
    {"label":"Tomorrow","value":"1489582800:1489669200","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":true},
    {"label":"Friday","value":"1489669200:1489755600","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":true},
    {"label":"Saturday","value":"1489755600:1489842000","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":true},
    {"label":"Sunday","value":"1489842000:1489928400","isRefined":false,"noRefinement":false}
]
```

This is caused by [itemHasRefinement](https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch.js/blob/v2/packages/react-instantsearch/src/connectors/connectMultiRange.js#L51) using the facets stats property to get the min and max values and basing the view on those rather than what the actual values are within the results.

**Bug: What browsers are impacted? Which versions?**
From what I can tell, all of them

**What project are you opening an issue for?**
- react-instantsearch

**What is the version you are using? Always use the latest one before opening a bug issue.**
```
    "react-instantsearch": "~3.2.1"
```
